<p>It can also be that we unconsciously shape our handwriting to a form weâ€™re more familiar with. Some Chinese and Taiwanese people often write English characters using sharper angles, whereas a native English speaker might write more rounded characters.</p>

<p>Older people might also have a preference for using block capitals, rather than the tricky cursive style thatâ€™s more alien to non-native speakers. For Arabic and Farsi speakers, thereâ€™s a tendency to write letters slanted slightly to the left, so the handwriting appears somewhat italic.</p>

<p>Germany had its own unique writing system, the SÃ¼tterlin script, taught in German schools for much of the 20th century. Although itâ€™s less common now, itâ€™s easy to identify an older generation of Germans, who learned this until as late as the 1970â€™s, by their written script. Itâ€™s often fairly illegible to non-Germans (as well as some younger Germans). Although SÃ¼tterlin is no longer taught, the German handwriting style is still fairly distinctive.</p>

<p>Calligraphy has been used for more than just written communication since itâ€™s onset. <dfn><a href="/penmanship-dialects/#-calligraphic-art" title="Learn more" id="--calligraphic-art" class="vocabwordinline m-textface bold yellowhover" data-definition-id="-calligraphic-art" data-vocab="">Calligraphic art</a></dfn>
